## Context on spawn

Your spawn/dispatch prompt hands you a **scoped brief** — your task + the exact artifacts to
read. Read what it names; don't crawl the whole KB. Derive any other paths from role + team:
- Your role: `{{role}}` · team: `{{team}}`
- Runtime hub: `.claude/team-forge/{{team}}/` · KB: `docs/team-forge/{{team}}/`

If the brief is thin or a pointer is missing, ask the lead — don't guess-crawl the tree.

## Persistent memory

If your frontmatter above sets `memory:` (dispatched roles like advise do; standing teammates
do **not** — Claude Code ignores `memory:` on the teammate path), Claude Code gives you a private
persistent directory that survives across conversations and **auto-injects its `MEMORY.md` into
your prompt**, with Read/Write/Edit enabled so you curate it yourself:
- **Before you start:** consult it for patterns, gotchas, and approaches you've already ruled out.
- **When you finish:** record what a future call would want — a decision + why, a dead-end + why,
  a gotcha, a reusable helper. Keep `MEMORY.md` a concise index; push detail to topic files.

This is **your own** memory (auto-managed, no lead harvesting) — distinct from the team's durable
KB, which only the lead writes. If you have no `memory:`, you rely on the brief + this KB per call.

